HashMap tricks that solve/work in 50% problems in java interviews

🔥 1. Frequency Map (MOST IMPORTANT)
When to use:

Counting

Duplicates

Anagrams

Map<Integer, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

for (int num : nums) {
    freq.put(num, freq.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
}
Problems:

Two Sum (variant)

Majority Element

Valid Anagram

🔥 2. Two Sum Pattern (value → index)
Idea:

Store what you’ve seen, check what you need.

Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    int need = target - nums[i];

    if (map.containsKey(need)) {
        return new int[]{map.get(need), i};
    }

    map.put(nums[i], i);
}
Works for:

Pair problems

Difference problems

Complement logic

🔥 3. Prefix Sum + HashMap (VERY POWERFUL)
When:

Subarray sum problems

Works even with negatives

Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put(0, 1);

int sum = 0, count = 0;

for (int num : nums) {
    sum += num;

    if (map.containsKey(sum - k)) {
        count += map.get(sum - k);
    }

    map.put(sum, map.getOrDefault(sum, 0) + 1);
}
Problems:

Subarray Sum Equals K

Continuous Subarray Sum

🔥 4. Longest Subarray (Prefix + first occurrence)
Store first time you see a sum
Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put(0, -1);

int sum = 0, maxLen = 0;

for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    sum += nums[i];

    if (map.containsKey(sum - k)) {
        maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, i - map.get(sum - k));
    }

    map.putIfAbsent(sum, i);
}


🔥 5. Sliding Window + HashMap
For strings / distinct elements
Map<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
int left = 0;

for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
    char c = s.charAt(right);
    map.put(c, map.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);

    while (map.get(c) > 1) {
        char leftChar = s.charAt(left);
        map.put(leftChar, map.get(leftChar) - 1);
        left++;
    }
}
Problems:

Longest substring without repeating chars

At most K distinct

🔥 6. Grouping (VERY COMMON in Java interviews)
Map<Character, List<String>> map = new HashMap<>();

for (String s : strs) {
    char key = s.charAt(0);

    map.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(s);
}
Cleaner version (Streams):
Arrays.stream(strs)
      .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(s -> s.charAt(0)));


🔥 7. Sort + HashMap (when order matters)

Use map + sorting keys:

Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
// fill map

List<Integer> keys = new ArrayList<>(map.keySet());
Collections.sort(keys);


🔥 8. Top K Elements (Heap + HashMap)
Map<Integer, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

for (int n : nums)
    freq.put(n, freq.getOrDefault(n, 0) + 1);

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq =
    new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> freq.get(a) - freq.get(b));

for (int n : freq.keySet()) {
    pq.add(n);
    if (pq.size() > k) pq.poll();
}


🧠 Golden Rules (Interview Cheat Sheet)
✅ Always think:

“Can I store what I’ve seen?”
“Can I trade space for time?”
